1k0.title: What is Arbital?
1k0.clickbait: This is the home page for the entire website.
1k0.text:
Arbital is an ambitious effort to *solve online discussion.*  This is a large problem which requires solving many hard subproblems, and our initial prototype is focusing on *solving online explanation.*  We want to do for difficult explanations - and someday, complicated arguments in general - what Wikipedia did for centralizing humanity's knowledge of agreed-on simple facts.

If you want to know the population of Melbourne, [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melbourne Wikipedia has you covered].  If you look at the [Wikipedia page on Bayes's Theorem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem), it's clear that Wikipedia isn't trying to solve the problem of explaining things to people in general.  This isn't because Wikipedia is lazy, it's because there are new, hard technical and UI problems required to collaboratively write explanations that will work on many different readers.

If you check out [1zq Arbital's Guide to Bayes's Rule] and contrast that with the [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_rule Wikipedia entry on Bayes's Rule], you'll get a quick picture of the new direction Arbital is heading.  Our current prototype isn't feature-complete even for the job of "explaining things", but we expect that the current prototype already provides the best URL on the Internet if you need to point a readership (not just one individual) at an explanation of Bayes.

In turn, if we can solve the problem of centralizing 'explanations' - having a single URL for something like Bayes's Rule, at which you can point a realistic distribution of online readers with widely ranging levels of prior knowledge and desired levels of detail - then we've taken a big step toward eliminating some of the massive redundancy and lack of quality control in *arguments* or *the generation of new knowledge.*  This would involve new hard problems that aren't part of the minimum viable product we're currently targeting.  But even if we fail at that still more ambitious goal, just moving to a world with centralized explanations would be a massive change already - a world where, if you want to learn something complicated and difficult, there's the same obvious first step as there is today for looking up a publicly known fact on Wikipedia.

For more about what we're trying to do and why, you can read [260 here] about [260 Arbital's ambitions].

Since Arbital has not yet implemented the features (user karma and karma thresholds) to moderate open commenting and resolve editing conflicts, we've currently restricted commenting and editing on Arbital to require an invite code.  Similarly, at our prototype's present levels of scalability we prefer that you not post Arbital links to Hacker News or Reddit front-pages, but linking Arbital in online comments or forwarding links to friends is fine.

We're continuing to actively build out Arbital.  Are you an experienced programmer who wants to solve hard problems and fix online discussion?  Do you understand the vision behind Arbital and want to work on it as a designer?  Are you interested in getting involved with Arbital some other way? Talk to us: alexei@arbital.com.
